summary: I wasn't looking forward to be rescued by Captain Marvel, and that's not how I feel. I went in to enjoy a superhero movie, I was...
body: I wasn’t looking forward to be rescued by Captain Marvel, and that’s not how I feel. I went in to enjoy a superhero movie, I was excited because it would star a female lead, and I was hoping I wouldn’t feel patronised or put on a pedestal. And on those accounts, this film rocked. Plus there was a cat. win win.

caption:
1hr 30min into #CaptainMarvel so far and this is turning out to be the worst #Marvel #MCU movie so far. Give @wellhayley an #AgentCarter movie instead. Her #PeggyCarter TV show was amazing… and had much more flair, gripping action, and smart humour than #BrieLarson’s weak debut… and yes, I mean weaker than even the first #AntMan, which looking back was actually amazing compared to this. 20 minutes to go… can it redeem itself? Doubtful…

summary: Not all Skrulls are bad, not all Skrulls are good
body:
Not all Skrulls are bad, not all Skrulls are good

Kevin Feige himself said it. It should be common knowledge, but O.K.

Yes, Talos’ comic counterpart is evil while his MCU portrayal is not. Yes, we saw a dozen Skrulls seeking shelter, but we also didn’t see what truly caused the Kree-Skrull war.

Stop saying you’ve been fooled or that MCU did the Skrulls “wrongly”. You’ve only seen a few, they’re an entire species living across an entire Galaxy called Andromeda.

This is what happens during every war: some will hide to live peacefully and others will plot schemes to fight.

In fact, the only “known” Skrull we saw was Talos.

Plus, Talos never was the one who coordinated the Secret Invasion. It was Veranke. We haven’t seen her yet, now have we?

I repeat! Not every human is bad, not every human is good. Same for shape-shifters. 🖖
